<subSubSection id="27C89EE4281B0F16FD70715D8C27FABC" pageId="2" pageNumber="372" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="6F6DCD6F281B0F16FD70715D8C27FABC" blockId="2.[685,1173,778,1730]" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FD70715D8BD2FCD2" bold="true" box="[709,937,779,800]" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">Differential Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Males of 
<taxonomicName id="A8D2B6EC281B0F16FBBA715C8C11FCD2" authorityName="Pascoe" authorityYear="1887" box="[1039,1130,778,800]" class="Insecta" family="Ripiphoridae" genus="Aporrhipis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="372" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flexilis">
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FBBA715C8C11FCD2" box="[1039,1130,778,800]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">A. flexilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be separated from other 
<taxonomicName id="A8D2B6EC281B0F16FC2571708B81FCC9" baseAuthorityName="Bocakova" baseAuthorityYear="2005" box="[912,1018,806,827]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="372" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Calopterini">Calopterini</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A8D2B6EC281B0F16FB9371708CE8FCC9" box="[1062,1171,806,827]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="372" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Leptolycini">Leptolycini</taxonomicName>
with flabellate antennae by the following characters: from 
<taxonomicName id="A8D2B6EC281B0F16FD54710C8BAAFC82" authority="Pic, 1929" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1929" box="[737,977,858,880]" class="Insecta" family="Coleoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Flabellocaenia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="372" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FD54710C8B0BFC82" box="[737,880,858,880]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">Flabellocaenia</emphasis>
Pic, 1929
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="A8D2B6EC281B0F16FC68710D8C36FC82" box="[989,1101,859,880]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="372" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Leptolycini">Leptolycini</taxonomicName>
) by the absence of scaliform setae on the antennae (
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FBCF71208CF5FC79" box="[1146,1166,886,907]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">vs</emphasis>
. presence of scaliform setae on the antennae in 
<taxonomicName id="A8D2B6EC281B0F16FBD871D98B6DFC32" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1929" class="Insecta" family="Coleoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Flabellocaenia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="372" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FBD871D98B6DFC32" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">Flabellocaenia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and by antennomere III much larger than II (
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FD7271938AA1FC28" box="[711,730,965,986]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">vs</emphasis>
. antennomeres II and III small, subequal in size in 
<taxonomicName id="A8D2B6EC281B0F16FD1871898B4EFC07" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1929" box="[685,821,991,1013]" class="Insecta" family="Coleoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Flabellocaenia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="372" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FD1871898B4EFC07" box="[685,821,991,1013]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">Flabellocaenia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); from 
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FC3C71898C51FC07" box="[905,1066,991,1013]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">Pseudoacroleptus</emphasis>
Pic, 1911 (
<taxonomicName id="A8D2B6EC281B0F16FD0671AC8B66FBFD" box="[691,797,1018,1039]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="372" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Leptolycini">Leptolycini</taxonomicName>
) by the flabellum of antennomere III short, subequal to the length of the main stem (
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FBFB76438C1AFBD8" box="[1102,1121,1045,1066]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">vs</emphasis>
. very long, many times longer than the stem in 
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FB9276798AA5FBAD" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">Pseudoacroleptus</emphasis>
); from 
<taxonomicName id="A8D2B6EC281B0F16FC9C761F8C5BFBAD" authority="Bourgeois, 1886" authorityName="Bourgeois" authorityYear="1886" box="[809,1056,1097,1119]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Acroleptus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="372" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FC9C761F8BFFFBAD" box="[809,900,1097,1119]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">Acroleptus</emphasis>
Bourgeois, 1886
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="A8D2B6EC281B0F16FB9A761C8CF6FBAD" baseAuthorityName="Bocakova" baseAuthorityYear="2005" box="[1071,1165,1098,1119]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="372" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Calopterini">Calopterini</taxonomicName>
/ 
<taxonomicName id="A8D2B6EC281B0F16FD1876328B6AFB8B" authorityName="Bocakova" authorityYear="2005" box="[685,785,1124,1145]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="372" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Acroleptina">Acroleptina</taxonomicName>
) by the convex frons (
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FC6B76338B94FB88" box="[990,1007,1125,1146]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">vs</emphasis>
. concave in 
<taxonomicName id="A8D2B6EC281B0F16FBD676328AA5FB66" authorityName="Bourgeois" authorityYear="1886" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Acroleptus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="372" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FBD676328AA5FB66" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">Acroleptus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and by the absence of a median longitudinal areola or cell (
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FD5876CC8A85FB5D" box="[749,766,1178,1199]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">vs</emphasis>
. presence of a median longitudinal areola or cell in 
<taxonomicName id="A8D2B6EC281B0F16FD7E76E58B97FB3B" authority="Bourgeois" authorityName="Bourgeois" box="[715,1004,1203,1225]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Acroleptus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="372" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chevrolati">
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FD7E76E58BFDFB3B" box="[715,902,1203,1225]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">Acroleptus chevrolati</emphasis>
Bourgeois
</taxonomicName>
); from 
<taxonomicName id="A8D2B6EC281B0F16FB8D76E58BF0FB16" authority="Bocak, 2001" authorityName="Bocak" authorityYear="2001" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Leptolycus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="372" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Baholycus">
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FB8D76E58CEFFB3B" box="[1080,1172,1203,1225]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">Leptolycus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FD0176988B77FB16" box="[692,780,1230,1252]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">Baholycus</emphasis>
) Bocák, 2001
</taxonomicName>
by the elytra with four elytral costae, reticulated and non-dehiscent (
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FC4676BF8C7FFB0C" box="[1011,1028,1257,1278]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">vs</emphasis>
. elytra with two elytral costae, non-reticulated and dehiscent in 
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FB8177558CF7FAEB" box="[1076,1164,1283,1305]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">Baholycus</emphasis>
) and by the absence of pronotal stemmata 
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FB9277488C2CFAC1" box="[1063,1111,1310,1331]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="0B43B09E281B0F16FBEA77488A9DFABC" author="Miller, R. S." pageId="2" pageNumber="372" refId="ref2850" refString="Miller, R. S. 1991. A revision of the Leptolycini (Coleoptera: Lycidae) with a discussion of paedomorphosis. PhD dissertation, The Ohio State University, Columbus, OH." type="book" year="1991">Miller (1991)</bibRefCitation>
(
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FD46776F8B7FFABC" box="[755,772,1337,1358]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">vs</emphasis>
. four pronotal stemmata in 
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FC4D776E8C2BFABC" box="[1016,1104,1336,1358]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">Baholycus</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="27C89EE4281B0F17FD7077028CD1F930" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="373" pageId="2" pageNumber="372" type="description">
<paragraph id="6F6DCD6F281B0F17FD7077028CD1F930" blockId="2.[685,1173,778,1730]" lastBlockId="3.[707,1194,1443,1730]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="373" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FD7077028B36FA9B" bold="true" box="[709,845,1364,1385]" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">Redescription.</emphasis>
Male. Brown, with humeral portion lighter, yellowish (
<figureCitation id="F7E9D1EA281B0F16FCFB77388BDAFA71" box="[846,929,1390,1411]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[197,236,1329,1348]" captionTargetBox="[177,1188,196,1311]" captionTargetId="figure-164@3.[175,1190,194,1313]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 1–4. Aporrhipis flexilis. 1) Holotype (deposited at the Natural History Museum), dorsal habitus; 2) Specimen deposited at the Carnegie Museum dorsal habitus; 3) Pronotum and dorsal view of head (specimen deposited at the Carnegie Museum); 4) Head, frontal view (specimen deposited at the Carnegie Museum)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5382752" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5382752/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">Figs. 1, 2</figureCitation>
). Body densely setose, with brown, decumbent pubescence. Length (pronotum + elytra) 4.5–5.0 mm.Width (across humeri) 
<quantity id="A82A608A281B0F16FBA777F58CEAFA4A" box="[1042,1169,1443,1465]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="8.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="372" unit="mm" value="0.09" valueMax="0.1" valueMin="0.08">0.08–0.10 mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281B0F16FD1877E88A9DFA21" bold="true" box="[685,742,1470,1491]" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">Head:</emphasis>
Small, as long as wide, wider behind eyes, with gibbous prominence on anterior portion, frons shallowly concave, posteriorly partially covered by pronotum, hypognathous (
<figureCitation id="F7E9D1EA281B0F16FC80745B8B11F9D0" box="[821,874,1549,1570]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[197,236,1329,1348]" captionTargetBox="[177,1188,196,1311]" captionTargetId="figure-164@3.[175,1190,194,1313]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 1–4. Aporrhipis flexilis. 1) Holotype (deposited at the Natural History Museum), dorsal habitus; 2) Specimen deposited at the Carnegie Museum dorsal habitus; 3) Pronotum and dorsal view of head (specimen deposited at the Carnegie Museum); 4) Head, frontal view (specimen deposited at the Carnegie Museum)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5382752" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5382752/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="372">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Eyes rounded, moderately large, anterolaterally projecting,coarsely granulate, interocular distance approximately 1.5X eye width. Maxillary palp 4-segmented, palpomere I short, II enlarged, as long as III+IV, III short, IV acuminate, longer than preceding. Labial palp 3-segmented, first 2 palpomeres short, last acuminate and strongly setose. Mandibles not reduced, strongly hooked apically. Anterior margin of epistoma emarginate, broadly oval, labrum short, trapezoidal (
<figureCitation id="F7E9D1EA281A0F17FDC577E888C1FA1F" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[197,236,1329,1348]" captionTargetBox="[177,1188,196,1311]" captionTargetId="figure-164@3.[175,1190,194,1313]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 1–4. Aporrhipis flexilis. 1) Holotype (deposited at the Natural History Museum), dorsal habitus; 2) Specimen deposited at the Carnegie Museum dorsal habitus; 3) Pronotum and dorsal view of head (specimen deposited at the Carnegie Museum); 4) Head, frontal view (specimen deposited at the Carnegie Museum)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5382752" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5382752/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="373">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Antennae inserted in gibbous prominence at anterior portion of head (
<figureCitation id="F7E9D1EA281A0F17FE8C77A589F1F9FA" box="[313,394,1522,1544]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[197,236,1329,1348]" captionTargetBox="[177,1188,196,1311]" captionTargetId="figure-164@3.[175,1190,194,1313]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 1–4. Aporrhipis flexilis. 1) Holotype (deposited at the Natural History Museum), dorsal habitus; 2) Specimen deposited at the Carnegie Museum dorsal habitus; 3) Pronotum and dorsal view of head (specimen deposited at the Carnegie Museum); 4) Head, frontal view (specimen deposited at the Carnegie Museum)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5382752" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5382752/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="373">Figs.1–3</figureCitation>
), 11-segmented, antennomeres III–X flabellate on outer portion; antennomere I subconical, as long as antennomeres III–IV, antennomere II minute, antennomere III subequal in length to IV, both with flabellum subequal to branch, antennomeres V–XI slightly increasing in length, flabellum much longer than branches, about 5X longer. 
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281A0F17FE0374C48A67F955" bold="true" box="[438,540,1682,1703]" pageId="3" pageNumber="373">Pronotum:</emphasis>
Trapezoidal, transverse,wider posteriorly; margins prominent; anterior angles acute; with a weak, longitudinal carina (
<figureCitation id="F7E9D1EA281A0F17FBD277F58CE6FA4A" box="[1127,1181,1443,1464]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[197,236,1329,1348]" captionTargetBox="[177,1188,196,1311]" captionTargetId="figure-164@3.[175,1190,194,1313]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 1–4. Aporrhipis flexilis. 1) Holotype (deposited at the Natural History Museum), dorsal habitus; 2) Specimen deposited at the Carnegie Museum dorsal habitus; 3) Pronotum and dorsal view of head (specimen deposited at the Carnegie Museum); 4) Head, frontal view (specimen deposited at the Carnegie Museum)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5382752" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5382752/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="373">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
); hypomeron concave. 
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281A0F17FC3077E88B93FA21" bold="true" box="[901,1000,1470,1491]" pageId="3" pageNumber="373">Scutellum:</emphasis>
Bifurcate posteriorly, posterior margins rounded. 
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281A0F17FC04778E8B88FA1F" bold="true" box="[945,1011,1496,1517]" pageId="3" pageNumber="373">Elytra:</emphasis>
Elongate, irregularly reticulate, parallel-sided, about 8X longer than pronotum, slightly surpassing abdominal apex, with 4 distinct longitudinal costae (
<figureCitation id="F7E9D1EA281A0F17FCC1747E8BB0F9CF" box="[884,971,1576,1597]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[197,236,1329,1348]" captionTargetBox="[177,1188,196,1311]" captionTargetId="figure-164@3.[175,1190,194,1313]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 1–4. Aporrhipis flexilis. 1) Holotype (deposited at the Natural History Museum), dorsal habitus; 2) Specimen deposited at the Carnegie Museum dorsal habitus; 3) Pronotum and dorsal view of head (specimen deposited at the Carnegie Museum); 4) Head, frontal view (specimen deposited at the Carnegie Museum)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5382752" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5382752/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="373">Figs. 1, 2</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="5DA6117D281A0F17FC68747E8C59F9CF" bold="true" box="[989,1058,1576,1597]" pageId="3" pageNumber="373">Venter:</emphasis>
Prosternum Yshaped, posterior margin rounded, laterally reaching hypomeron. Mesoventrite trapezoidal, posteriorly reaching anterior margin of metaventrite; mesanepisternum elongate; mesepimeron short and slender, with conspicuous row of setae; mesospiracles not visible.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
